HEADWORD: Neoimpressionism
<hw>Ne`o*im*pres"sion*ism</hw>
<pr>(n⟦emac⟧`⟦osl⟧*⟦icr⟧m*pr⟦ecr⟧sh"⟦ucr⟧n*⟦icr⟧z'm)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<fld>(Painting)</fld> <def>A theory or practice which is a further
development, on more rigorously scientific lines, of the theory and
practice of Impressionism, originated by <person>George Seurat</person>
(1859-91), and carried on by <person>Paul Signac</person> (1863- -) and
others. Its method is marked by the laying of pure primary colors in
minute dots upon a white ground, any given line being produced by a
variation in the proportionate quantity of the primary colors employed.
This method is also known as <altname>
